Introduction¶

a. Goal of project¶

  • In this project, we will analyze the TMDB-Movies Dataset by using the Python libraries NumPy, pandas, and Matplotlib.

  • Some questions about this dataset:

    • Research Question 1. Which films have the highest revenue over the time? Who are the most popular directors and casts in the highest revenue films and over time?

    • Research Question 2: How is the trend of genres of films over the time?

    • Research Question 3: The trend of runtime over time and its relationship with revenue?

    • Research Question 4: The trend of budget and revenue over time and relationship between budget and revenue?

    • Research Question 5: The relationship among vote_count, vote_average, and revenue_adjusted

b. Assessing data¶

At the first look, we can see that the data hat 21 columns and 10866 rows.

1.We donot need all of these information to analyze so we drop some unnec3essary information such as imdb_id, budget, revenue, homepage, tagline,overview, popularity. Here we only keep the budget_adj and revenue_adj because it will give a better view for the comparion between years. And I dont understand what is about popularity so I will not choose it to analyze.

2.Through the input.head() we can see that there some quality and tidiness problems in this dataset:

  • quality problems:
    • due to input.info() we can see that the data type of release_date
    • There are a lot of 0 value in columns revenue_adj, budget_adj, runtime, which are not reasonable. So we keep only the film having value in those columns larger than 0 are kept.
  • tidiness problems:
    • Check the duplicated() and find that there has 1 duplicated row
    • There are some columns such as cast, director, genres, production_companies having variables in 1 colum

c. Data Cleaning¶

# 1. drop some unnecessary columns: imdb_id, budget, revenue, homepage, tagline,overview
input= input0.drop(columns=['imdb_id', 'budget', 'revenue', 'homepage', 'tagline','overview'])
In [51]:
# 2. cleaning quality problems
input['release_date']=pd.to_datetime(input['release_date'])
input['revenue_adj'].replace(0,np.NaN, inplace =True)
input['budget_adj'].replace(0,np.NaN, inplace =True)
input['runtime'].replace(0,np.NaN, inplace =True)
input = input.dropna(axis=0,subset=['revenue_adj','budget_adj','runtime'])
In [465]:
# 3. cleaing tidiness problems
input.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)
input_new = (input.genres.str.split('|', expand= True).add_prefix('genres_'))
input_genres0=pd.get_dummies(input_new['genres_0'])
input_genres1=pd.get_dummies(input_new['genres_1'])
input_genres2=pd.get_dummies(input_new['genres_2'])
input_genres3=pd.get_dummies(input_new['genres_3'])
input_genres4=pd.get_dummies(input_new['genres_4'])

df_col = pd.concat([input['id'],input_genres0,input_genres1,input_genres2,input_genres3,input_genres4], axis=1)
input_genres =df_col.groupby(level=0, axis=1).sum()

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Tip: Now that you've trimmed and cleaned your data, you're ready to move on to exploration. Research Question 1: Which films have the highest revenue over the time? Who are the most popular directors and casts in the highest revenue films and over time?¶

With the Table 1 following, we can see that Top 10 highest revenue film over the time. Out of them, Avatar released 2009 places at the place 1, followings are StarWars 1977 and Titanic 1997. At this table, we have some first view about the adjusted budget, adjusted revenue and the casts of these high revenue films.

In Table 2: We can see clearly that most of the highest revenue films are Adventure, Action, Science Fiction. Other kinds of genres specially Comedy, Romance and so accounts only a small part, or perhaps play only a not-very- important role for such a successful film. However when we look into Table 3, We can see genres like drama, comedy at the Top 2 of the number of films that have been made over time.

For the cast in these films, I list only some casts, but acctually there more than 42 casts playing in these films. Most of them are very famous. Meanwhile in Table 3, the Top 10 popular casts over time are shown with the number of films they played.

In Table 2, we can see the name of director, who have made the highest revenue films, whereas in Table 3, the most popular directors over time are also shown. Out of them, James Cameron and Steven Spielberg are of course the most famous ones.

Research Question 2: How is the trend of genres of films over the time?¶

With the line chart, we can see clearly trend of genres over time. As mentioned above, drame are the favorite one of directors, this kind of films are made more and more from years to years. The followings are comedy, thriller and action.

Overally, there are an increasing trend over time in making film. However, in chart 1, we can see that the peak of films was in 2005-2010 with the highest number of all kinds of films. Most of genres are in downward trend now in making films, specially with action films, only drama seems to going to be back its highest point soon.

Research Question 3: The trend of runtime over time and its relationship with revenue?¶

With Chart 2, we can see the trend of runtime over years, it is a decreasing trend in runtime, its plunged to the bottom in the later 80s and from then, most of films have average runtime of around 100 minutes which can be seen clearly in Chart 3.

In Chart 4, we can see a relationship between runtime and revenue. We can see that most of film having good revenue (revenue > 1e9) have runtime between 120 and 200 minutes.

Research Question 4: The trend of budget and revenue over time and relationship between budget and revenue?¶

In Chart 5, it is interesting that the adjusted revenue of films before 80s are higher than the one of nowaday films. However it can be understandable because the number of films nowaday is quite larger than before, the revenue gap between films are also quite high, so it is possible that the average revenue of a film nowaday is lower than before. Meanwhile the budget spending for 1 film seems to be quite stable over time. It stays always under USD 1e8 (at around 4.4e07).

Chart 6, Chart 7, Chart 8 give us a better view about the relationship between budget and revenue. With chart 6, we can see that the revenue are not always parrarel with budget. There are films with small budget but gaining high revenue. Some of them are Star War or The Exorcist. In contrast, some films like The Warrior's Way having the largest budget over time, but revenue is very low.

Research Question 5: The relationship among vote_count, vote_average, and revenue_adjusted¶

Chart 9 shows the relationship between vote_count and revenue. it is a normale thinking that the more vote_count from audience a film has, the better revenue can that film gain. It is the same with vote_average. But it is not always true. Look at the chart, it can be seen clearly that although the vote_count and vote_average have a strong positive correlation, but there are some films having a lot of vote_count as well as a high vote_average still getting a very bad revenue.

plt.title('\n \n Chart 11: vote_average and adjusted revenue', 
          loc='center', fontsize=12, fontweight=0)

plt.subplot(2,2,4)
plt.scatter(x = input[['vote_average']], y = input['revenue_adj'], s= 0.04*input['vote_count'] ,label=input['vote_count'], alpha=0.5)
plt.xlabel('vote_average', fontsize = 12)
plt.ylabel('Revenue_adjusted', fontsize = 12)
plt.title('Chart 11: Relationship among \n vote_average,vote_count and adjusted revenue', 
          loc='center', fontsize=12, fontweight=0)
fig.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.2)
fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.4)
plt.show()

Conclusions¶

1. Conclusion¶

In this project, we have performed all steps involved in a typical data analysis process. Beginning with placing questions which we wan to get the answer with a given dataset. Then we do data wrangling which includes data assessing, data cleaning to investigate problems. And therefore some questions about the revenue, trend of genres, runtime, revenue were placed at the beginning. Then, we also analyze some relationship with revenue as the dependent variable and its relationship with some other variables such as genres, runtime, vote_count, vote_average. After all, we can fortunately answer the questions posted at the beginning.

2. Limitation¶

With the visualization and some commands using Python libraries. We can have at first some aspects of dataset. For example, we can see almost of these variables have some impacts on revenue, but the assessing of how strong and how exact they are, were not included in this scope of project. With some more practical statistics such as regression for number variables and logistic regression for categorical variable, perhaps we can have more exact information about dataset.
